down from the ledge.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; As I was walking out (empty-handed), I noticed that Best Buy has taken
&gt; a page from the Fry's playbook, and set up ONE line which leads to the
&gt; rows of cashiers. They very cleverly hide the line behind a high wall
&gt; so you can't see how long the line is until you're practically IN the
&gt; line; I guess this is carefully calculated to minimize the number of
&gt; people who see the long line, say &quot;fuck that noise,&quot; and walk out.

&gt; Unfortunately, despite the long line, there are only FOUR checkout
&gt; stations - and only three of them were manned. Judging by the length
&gt; of the line, it looked like a good 20 or 30 minute wait.

"/> I worked briefly on a project while still at BBY where we used
queueing theory to model the checkout lines. We found that you
get through far quicker when there is one line feeding the cash
registers than if there are more than one line. It really helps
when you get one register hung up for a reason...the folks who are
waiting can get through on one of the other registers without
having to go to the end of another line.

BBY has a pretty nice POS system. They do pretty well in that
area of their business. As a result, a checkout does go pretty
quickly. I would be surprised if that line was 20 minutes. A
given customer can get through the checkout in a minute or so
unless they have something special, and most of the special
stuff is handled either at customer service or in the specific
departments these days.

-john-

